#Text=CHAPTER XII .
#Text=Alice ’s Evidence

#Text=‘ Here ! ’ cried Alice , quite forgetting in the flurry of the moment how large she had grown in the last few minutes , and she jumped up in such a hurry that she tipped over the jury-box with the edge of her skirt , upsetting all the jurymen on to the heads of the crowd below , and there they lay sprawling about , reminding her very much of a globe of goldfish she had accidentally upset the week before .

#Text=‘ Oh , I BEG your pardon ! ’ she exclaimed in a tone of great dismay , and began picking them up again as quickly as she could , for the accident of the goldfish kept running in her head , and she had a vague sort of idea that they must be collected at once and put back into the jury-box , or they would die .

#Text=‘ The trial cannot proceed , ’ said the King in a very grave voice , ‘ until all the jurymen are back in their proper places -- ALL , ’ he repeated with great emphasis , looking hard at Alice as he said do .

#Text=Alice looked at the jury-box , and saw that , in her haste , she had put the Lizard in head downwards , and the poor little thing was waving its tail about in a melancholy way , being quite unable to move .
#Text=She soon got it out again , and put it right ;
#Text=‘ not that it signifies much , ’ she said to herself ; ‘ I should think it would be QUITE as much use in the trial one way up as the other . ’

#Text=As soon as the jury had a little recovered from the shock of being upset , and their slates and pencils had been found and handed back to them , they set to work very diligently to write out a history of the accident , all except the Lizard , who seemed too much overcome to do anything but sit with its mouth open , gazing up into the roof of the court .
#Text=‘ What do you know about this business ? ’ the King said to Alice .
#Text=‘ Nothing , ’ said Alice .
#Text=‘ Nothing WHATEVER ? ’ persisted the King .
#Text=‘ Nothing whatever , ’ said Alice .
#Text=‘ That ’s very important , ’ the King said , turning to the jury .

#Text=They were just beginning to write this down on their slates , when the White Rabbit interrupted : ‘ UNimportant , your Majesty means , of course , ’ he said in a very respectful tone , but frowning and making faces at him as he spoke .
#Text=‘ UNimportant , of course , I meant , ’ the King hastily said , and went on to himself in an undertone ,
#Text=‘ important -- unimportant -- unimportant -- important -- ’ as if he were trying which word sounded best .
#Text=Some of the jury wrote it down ‘ important , ’ and some ‘ unimportant . ’
#Text=Alice could see this , as she was near enough to look over their slates ;
#Text=‘ but it does n’t matter a bit , ’ she thought to herself .
#Text=At this moment the King , who had been for some time busily writing in his note-book , cackled out ‘ Silence ! ’ and read out from his book , ‘ Rule Forty-two .
#Text=ALL PERSONS MORE THAN A MILE HIGH TO LEAVE THE COURT . ’
#Text=Everybody looked at Alice .
#Text=‘ I’M not a mile high , ’ said Alice .
#Text=‘ You are , ’ said the King .
#Text=‘ Nearly two miles high , ’ added the Queen .
#Text=‘ Well , I sha n’t go , at any rate , ’ said Alice :
#Text=‘ besides , that ’s not a regular rule : you invented it just now . ’
#Text=‘ It ’s the oldest rule in the book , ’ said the King .
#Text=‘ Then it ought to be Number One , ’ said Alice .
#Text=The King turned pale , and shut his note-book hastily .
#Text=‘ Consider your verdict , ’ he said to the jury , in a low , trembling voice .
#Text=‘ There ’s more evidence to come yet , please your Majesty , ’ said the White Rabbit , jumping up in a great hurry ;
#Text=‘ this paper has just been picked up . ’
#Text=‘ What ’s in it ? ’ said the Queen .
#Text=‘ I have n’t opened it yet , ’ said the White Rabbit , ‘ but it seems to be a letter , written by the prisoner to -- to somebody . ’
#Text=‘ It must have been that , ’ said the King , ‘ unless it was written to nobody , which is n’t usual , you know . ’
#Text=‘ Who is it directed to ? ’ said one of the jurymen .
#Text=‘ It is n’t directed at all , ’ said the White Rabbit ; ‘ in fact , there ’s nothing written on the OUTSIDE . ’
#Text=He unfolded the paper as he spoke , and added ‘ It is n’t a letter , after all : it ’s a set of verses . ’
#Text=‘ Are they in the prisoner ’s handwriting ? ’ asked another of the jurymen .
#Text=‘ No , they ’re not , ’ said the White Rabbit , ‘ and that ’s the queerest thing about it . ’
#Text=( The jury all looked puzzled . )
#Text=‘ He must have imitated somebody else ’s hand , ’ said the King .
#Text=( The jury all brightened up again . )
#Text=‘ Please your Majesty , ’ said the Knave , ‘ I did n’t write it , and they ca n’t prove I did : there ’s no name signed at the end . ’
#Text=‘ If you did n’t sign it , ’ said the King , ‘ that only makes the matter worse .
#Text=You MUST have meant some mischief , or else you ’d have signed your name like an honest man . ’
#Text=There was a general clapping of hands at this : it was the first really clever thing the King had said that day .
#Text=‘ That PROVES his guilt , ’ said the Queen .
#Text=‘ It proves nothing of the sort ! ’ said Alice .
#Text=‘ Why , you do n’t even know what they ’re about ! ’
#Text=‘ Read them , ’ said the King .
#Text=The White Rabbit put on his spectacles .
#Text=‘ Where shall I begin , please your Majesty ? ’ he asked .
#Text=‘ Begin at the beginning , ’ the King said gravely , ‘ and go on till you come to the end : then stop . ’
#Text=These were the verses the White Rabbit read : --
#Text=‘ They told me you had been to her , And mentioned me to him : She gave me a good character , But said I could not swim .
